<p>In <a href="https://www.jeremycherfas.net/blog/printed-is-not-the-point">Printed is not the Point</a>, I encountered the following quote:</p>

<blockquote  class="h-cite">

What record are we leaving if the printed word is not the most interesting
creative work being developed?

<footer>&mdash;
<span class="p-author h-card">Naomi Duguid</span>
</footer>
</blockquote>

<p>I question that the â€œprinted wordâ€œ has ever been much of â€œthe most interesting
creative work being developed.â€  Consider the interesting and ephemeral [saucy]
puppet show, street protest, poetic recitation, dance routine, or concert.
Though perhaps â€œworkâ€ is carrying the burden?  As in the toil expressed?  Or the
concept enclosed?</p>
<p>But then again, the word â€œinterestingâ€ is one of those â€œeye of the beholderâ€
words.  The printed wordâ€™s super power is one of slow moving transport: across
time and space.  Ideas bound and encoded for transportâ€”of atomic symbols
